          <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Seasonal Bird Migration Guide</h1>

          <p class="mb-4">
            Bird migration is one of nature's most impressive phenomena. Each
            year, billions of birds travel thousands of miles between breeding
            and wintering grounds, navigating by stars, landmarks, Earth's
            magnetic field, and even their sense of smell.
          </p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">
            Understanding Migration Timing
          </h2>

          <p class="mb-4">
            Migration follows a predictable calendar in most regions, though
            exact timing can vary by species and weather conditions:
          </p>

          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
            <li>
              <strong>Spring Migration (March-May):</strong> Birds travel north
              to breeding grounds. Waterbirds and raptors often lead, followed
              by insect-eaters like warblers and flycatchers.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Fall Migration (August-November):</strong> Birds travel
              south to wintering grounds. Generally more spread out than spring
              migration, with shorebirds often starting in July.
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Migration Hotspots</h2>

          <p class="mb-4">
            Certain geographic features concentrate migrating birds, making
            these locations excellent for observation:
          </p>

          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
            <li>
              <strong>Coastlines:</strong> Many birds follow coastlines as
              navigational guides.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Ridges and Mountain Passes:</strong> Migrating raptors use
              thermal updrafts along ridges.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Major Waterways:</strong> Rivers provide navigation routes
              and rest stops.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Peninsulas and Land Bridges:</strong> Birds concentrate
              where land narrows.
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">
            Tips for Observing Migration
          </h2>

          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
            <li>
              <strong>Time of Day:</strong> Dawn is best for songbirds; hawks
              often migrate mid-morning to afternoon.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Weather:</strong> Check forecasts for conditions that
              trigger migratory movements. Birds often move after cold fronts in
              fall and warm fronts in spring.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Night Migration:</strong> Many birds migrate at night. On
              clear nights in migration season, try watching the moon with
              binoculars to observe silhouettes passing by.
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">
            Seasonal Guide to Migrating Species
          </h2>

          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-6 mb-3">
            Spring Migration Highlights
          </h3>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
            <li>
              <strong>March:</strong> Waterfowl, early songbirds like Eastern
              Phoebes and Tree Swallows
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>April:</strong> Many sparrows, kinglets, early warblers,
              vireos, thrushes
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>May:</strong> Peak warbler migration, flycatchers,
              tanagers, orioles, grosbeaks
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-6 mb-3">Fall Migration Highlights</h3>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
            <li>
              <strong>July-August:</strong> Shorebirds, early warblers in
              non-breeding plumage
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>September:</strong> Peak for many songbirds, including
              warblers, vireos, thrushes
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>October:</strong> Sparrows, kinglets, late thrushes,
              increasing waterfowl
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>November:</strong> Waterfowl, late sparrows, winter
              finches, northern raptors
            </li>
          </ul>

          <p class="mt-8 mb-4">
            Migration is a vulnerable time for birds. You can help by keeping
            cats indoors during peak migration, turning off unnecessary lights
            at night to prevent disorientation, and supporting habitat
            conservation efforts along migratory routes.
          </p>
        </article>

